modules.description: Creates a property with a specified name and value, used to track configuration or state during test runs. Represents key-value pairs where both the identifier and content are strings. Stores environment variables or test parameters for later retrieval or logging.

Creates test result records for errors, failures, skips, and passes, each containing structured metadata such as test name, class, execution time, and descriptive messages. Operates on string-based identifiers, floating-point durations, and custom error/failure types to represent test outcomes. Used to generate structured test reports with detailed status information for individual test cases.

Creates a testsuite with attributes such as name, package, timestamp, hostname, and system output/error. Adds test cases and properties to the testsuite. Used to collect and structure test execution data for reporting or analysis.

Generates JUnit XML reports with typed functions for test results, including test cases, failures, and summaries. It works with structured data representing test outcomes, such as test names, durations, and error messages. Used to produce Jenkins-compatible test reports from OUnit and Alcotest test suites.

The module provides functions to construct and convert JUnit XML elements, including test cases, test suites, timestamps, and error/failure records, using structured data types like `testcase`, `testsuite`, and `failure`. It enables low-level manipulation of JUnit test result data, mapping internal representations to XML formats for reporting or integration with testing frameworks. Specific use cases include generating standardized test output for continuous integration systems or analyzing test execution details.

Encapsulates test execution data by combining test results, properties, and suite metadata into structured reports. Supports creating test cases with status, duration, and messages, along with adding key-value properties and organizing them into test suites with contextual attributes. Enables generating detailed JUnit-compatible output by aggregating individual test outcomes and associated configuration. For example, it can track a test's execution time, log environment variables, and compile all results into a single suite for reporting.
